00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:05.000
But do you know which of the following words means sausages in British English slang? Is it a booze, b-banger, or sea brunch?

21
00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:11.000
So, I actually know the answer to this question, so I'm not going to say. Otherwise, it will spoil it for our listeners.

22
00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:15.000
Okay, well, we'll all find out at the end of the programme.

23
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:23.000
Although most research agrees that plant-based foods are healthier than meat, it's also true that meat-free products are processed.

24
00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:32.000
To make meat-free sausages, for example, after the proteins are broken down, flavorings and colourings are added to reproduce the taste or texture of meat.

25
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:42.000
Corn, one of the best known brands of meat-free products uses micro-protein, a fungi-based protein similar to the fungi used in the fermentation of yogurt and bread.

26
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:50.000
So, what does listener Graham think? Let's find out as he talks to Gregford, presenter of BBC Radio 4's sliced bread.

27
00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Graham, listening to all this, you know, normally a fan of a meat sausage, your plant-based meat- alternative sausage curious that we're exploring today.

28
00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:05.000
What do you think about hearing about the sources of where they come from? What's your gut reaction to hearing that corn comes from a fungus?

29
00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:12.000
I have no problems with that, and it's just another form of protein, as far as I'm concerned, it's what's the healthiest.

30
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:16.000
Yes, we will get to health, I think that's the big conversation for today.

31
00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:25.000
Greg asked Graham for his gut reaction. Your gut reaction is your opinion based on your initial feeling or instinct about something.

32
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:27.000
It can't be explained logically.

33
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:35.000
Actually, Graham doesn't mind that his sausage protein is a fungus, as long as it's healthy. He uses the phrase as far as I'm concerned,

34
00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:38.000
to indicate that he is giving his own opinion on the subject.

35
00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:47.000
Of course, healthy eating is important, but there are other factors influencing whether meat lovers like Graham could be persuaded to try plant-based alternatives.

36
00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:51.000
These include things like the taste, color, and texture of the sausage.

37
00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:56.000
In other words, whether a plant-based sausage looks and feels like real meat.

38
00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:01.000
Here's Greg discussing this point for BBC Radio for a program sliced bread.

39
00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:07.000
It's interesting, isn't it? Because my mum is a long time veggie, and we were talking about this, and she says,

40
00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:12.000
I don't want my alternative proteins to resemble meat, as one of the reasons she says she doesn't eat meat.

41
00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:17.000
But you Graham said you do want your plant-based sausage to resemble a pork sausage.

42
00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:26.000
Yeah, I'm obviously in the meat eater, but I do need a plant-based product to be similar in terms of flavour, texture, and appearance.

43
00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:35.000
Graham wants his plant-based sausages to resemble, meaning looks similar to meat, but that's not the case for Greg's mum, who's a long time veggie.

44
00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:39.000
A veggie is slang for a vegetarian, a person who doesn't eat meat.

45
00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:45.000
And the adjective long time describes someone who has been or done a particular thing for many years.

46
00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:49.000
So a long time veggie is someone who's been vegetarian for many years.

47
00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:58.000
Whether you want your veggie sausages to look, taste and feel like meat, or you prefer your protein from a plant, now there's every chance you'll find what you're looking for.

48
00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.000
And keep your body and planet healthy as well.

49
00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:05.000
Now isn't it time you revealed the answer to your question, Neil?

50
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:12.000
Yes, I asked what the British English slang word for sausages is, and what is it, Georgie?

51
00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:19.000
The answer is Banger, and we have a typical dish in the UK called Banger's and Mashed, which is sausages and Mashed.

52
00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:21.000
Love it, with gravy.

53
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:27.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned starting with Banger, a word which is slang for sausage.

54
00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:33.000
Your gut reaction is your opinion about something based on instinctive feelings, not logic or reason.

55
00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:38.000
The phrase as far as I'm concerned can be used to give your opinion about something.

56
00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:41.000
To resemble means to look or be similar to something.

57
00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:45.000
A veggie is slang for a vegetarian, someone who doesn't eat meat.

58
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:52.000
And finally, the adjective long time can be used to say that someone has done a particular thing for many years.

